Clodius was twice married, first to Pinaria and asterward to Ful· via: He lest a son, Publius, and a daughter. He inherited no property from his father. Besides what he obtained by less honest means, he received some moneys by legacies, and by letting one of his houses on the Palatine. He also received a considerable dowry with his wife Fulvia. He was the owner of two houses on the Palatine Hill, an estate near Alba, and considerable possessione in Etruria, near Lake Prelius. His personal appearance was effemi- nate, and neither handsome nor commanding. That he wasa man ³ of great energy and ability there can be little question; still less, that his character was of the most profligate kind. Cicero himself admits that he possessed considerable eloquence.
